title: For Sale:  Old Webley WP 320 Pocket Revolver
postcontent: This is a very old Webley and Scott LTD model Wp320. According to the official Webley page, they were discontinued in the 1930s. It also shows the serial number range but strangely, this one has a number that is 96 higher than the highest one listed. All numbers match on this old gal, even on the back side of the grips. Overall finish is quite good but does have some pitting on the cylinder. This thing has been sitting in a night stand drawer for about 6 decades that I know of. Before that though I do not know the history. The grips are perfect. The cylinder probably needs to be retimed if you want to shoot is a lot but it does lock up and fire as it should. The bore is excellent. Values on these things are all over the place. Most seem to bring 600-800 at auction although the Blue Book of Values shows it at only 400 dollars at 60%. Other than the pitting here I mentioned before the blueing is quite nice. No gouges, scratches, chips, etc. All markings are bright and very easily read. The only ammo I have left for it is a partial box , 38 rounds, of Remington 82 grain .32 Long Colt lead. I have fired it 5 times and it functioned as it should but that is as far as I have gone with it. I don't think any actual .320 ammo has been produced since the 1930s. I am selling this for a family friend who has owned it for well over 60 years and has not fired it in all that time. It just sat in a drawer by her bed. We are looking for a cash sale but feel free to offer up trades. If it is something that I can use myself I will keep it and pay her for the Webley. She is in her 90s now and no longer has a need for this or any other guns for that matter. Thank you for looking. Armslist only allows 3 pics but I can take as many as you want and send them to you upon request.

title: For Sale:  Upgraded Remington 700 VTR .308
postcontent:
Installed Hogue Heavy Barrel Aluminum Pillar bed stock (MSRP $149).  All screws torqued to factory specifications on all parts.  Recoil lug has been glass bedded.  Sighted in (100yds) Bushnell Bone Collector 3-9 scope (MSRP $130).  Harris 6-9HBR Bi-Pod (MSRP $75). Leupold 2 piece scope mount and rings (MSRP $110).  Barrel is free floated (see picture below).
 I spent lots of range time developing hand loads for this rifle.  Best round for this particular rifle is the Nosler .30 Caliber 150 gr Ballistic Tip and 42.5 gr. of VintaVuori N140 powder.  I will no longer need the hand loads I still have and they go with the rifle (50 rounds plus case) as they are tailored for it.  Amazingly, the second most accurate round I have fired out of this rifle is PMC Bronze 147gr.  It’s a fairly inexpensive round good for target shooting or varmint hunting.  And the handloads should last you a long time for hunting bigger game.  This rifle is easily capable of sub MOA groups at 100 yds.  Below is a 3 round group the last time I shot this rifle (ignore the flyer to the left).  And that was with the PMC ammo, not the hand loads.
This rifle has an integrated muzzle break…. It makes it much loader than a standard .308 Win.  The bonus is the triangle shaped barrel has more surface area so it dissipates heat faster.  The muzzle break reduces recoil (about the same recoil as a .243) and greatly reduces muzzle jump so follow-up shots are faster.  I have put about 250 rds through it and there are no dings, scratches, etc. anywhere on the rifle.
